Reflection Document:

    During the development of the IP Address Tracker application, I followed a step-by-step approach to build the interface and integrate external APIs.
 I began by setting up a React project using Vite and organizing the project structure into components such as the search bar, information card, and map view.
 This modular approach helped keep the code manageable and easier to debug.
 I implemented a search form that allows users to enter an IP address or domain, which then sends a request to the geolocation API to retrieve location data.
 The retrieved data is displayed in the information card and used to update the map location.

One of the main challenges I encountered was handling API errors and ensuring the map updated correctly after a user searched for a new IP address. 
Initially, the map would not refresh because the state values were not properly passed to the map component. 
I solved this issue by managing the data in a parent component and passing updated coordinates as props, allowing the map marker to re-render whenever new data was fetched. 
Another challenge involved aligning the layout so that the information card overlapped the header and map correctly. 
This was resolved by adjusting CSS properties such as positioning, margins, and z-index.

If I were to improve this project further, I would enhance responsiveness for smaller screens, improve error handling for invalid IP addresses, and add loading indicators
while fetching data. I would also refactor some styling into reusable classes and consider using environment variables for better API key management. 
Overall, this project helped me strengthen my understanding of React components, state management, API integration, and responsive design.

